e Python snippet if your search or control loop needs it.\nIf you include assistant text before a tool call, keep it short and use it to update the world model. Helpful optional prefixes are `World model:`, `Goal model:`, `Action model:`, `Recent findings:`, `Open questions:`, `Plan:`, and `Cross-level notes:`.\nWhen calling `python`, emit exactly the tool-call format shown elsewhere in this prompt for this model. Use only that format; do not add markdown fences, prose wrappers, or alternate tool-call syntax. Do not quote or place tool-call markup inside explanatory text; when you decide to call the tool, emit the tool call itself.\nIf you use MOUSE, include integer row and col arguments.\nEFFICIENCY BUDGET \u2014 your score on each level is (baseline_actions / your_actions)^2, so every wasted action costs you quadratically.\nLevel 1: you have used 2 of about 39 target actions so far.", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "THINKING", "content": "Let me check what changed after DOWN.", "kind": "reasoning", "inContext": false}, {"label": "TOOL CALL: python", "content": "<tool_call>\n<function=python>\n<parameter=code>\n# Compare by color after DOWN\ndef get_by_color(nodes, color):\n    for n in nodes:\n        if n['color'] == color:\n            rows = [p[0] for p in n['boundary']]\n            cols = [p[1] for p in n['boundary']]\n            return (min(rows), max(rows), min(cols), max(cols), n['pixels'])\n    return None\n\nbefore = last_transition.before_frame.segmentation['nodes']\nafter = current_frame.segmentation['nodes']\n\ncolors = ['N', 'O', 'c', 'M', 'b', 'Y', 'w']\nfor color in colors:\n    b = get_by_color(before, color)\n    a = get_by_color(after, color)\n    if b and a:\n        if b != a:\n            print(f\"  {color}: {b} -> {a}\")\n        else:\n            print(f\"  {color}: unchanged {b}\")\n</parameter>\n</function>\n</tool_call>", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "TOOL RESULT: python", "content": "N: (0, 0, 0, 61, 62) -> (0, 0, 0, 59, 60)\n  O: unchanged (1, 59, 0, 63, 3508)\n  c: unchanged (1, 3, 36, 39, 12)\n  M: unchanged (4, 7, 36, 39, 16)\n  b: (16, 19, 16, 35, 80) -> (20, 23, 16, 35, 80)\n  Y: unchanged (52, 59, 16, 27, 80)\n  w: unchanged (60, 63, 0, 63, 256)", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "THINKING", "content": "After DOWN:\n- N (green bar) shrank again: cols 0-61 -> 0-59 (lost 2 more pixels)\n- b (blue) moved down: rows 16-19 -> 20-23 (shifted +4 rows)\nSo arrow keys move the blue rectangle by 4 pixels in the direction pressed, and each move costs 2 pixels of the green bar. The green bar started at 64 pixels, so we have about 32 moves before it runs out.\nCurrent blue position: rows 20-23, cols 16-35\nYellow blocks are at rows 52-59, cols 16-27 and cols 40-51 (wait, let me re-check since there are two Y objects)\nActually, the get_by_color function only returns the first match. Let me check both yellow blocks.\nThe goal is likely to move the blue rectangle onto the yellow blocks. Let me try to figure out the best path. Blue is currently at rows 20-23, cols 16-35. The left yellow block is at rows 52-59, cols 16-27. \nTo reach the left yellow block, I need to go down. But I need to be careful about the green bar. Let me also try SPACE to see what it does.\nActually, let me first understand the full layout better and try SPACE.", "kind": "reasoning", "inContext": false}, {"label": "TOOL CALL: python", "content": "<tool_call>\n<function=python>\n<parameter=code>\n# Check both yellow blocks and try SPACE\nseg = current_frame.segmentation['nodes']\nfor n in seg:\n    if n['color'] == 'Y':\n        rows = [p[0] for p in n['boundary']]\n        cols = [p[1] for p in n['boundary']]\n        print(f\"Y block: rows {min(rows)}-{max(rows)}, cols {min(cols)}-{max(cols)}, pixels={n['pixels']}\")\n\n# Also check blue current position\nfor n in seg:\n    if n['color'] == 'b':\n        rows = [p[0] for p in n['boundary']]\n        cols = [p[1] for p in n['boundary']]\n